The LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a project that involves using an Arduino board to read temperature from a temperature sensor and display it on an LCD screen. The system also uses a potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

To set up the system, the temperature sensor, such as the DS18B20 or LM35, is connected to the Arduino board. The analog output pin of the temperature sensor is connected to an analog input pin on the Arduino board, such as pin A0 [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The LCD screen is connected to the Arduino board via a LiquidCrystal I2C library, which can be installed through the Arduino IDE [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

The potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the LCD panel. One pin of the potentiometer is connected to the VCC pin on the Arduino board, while the other pin is connected to pin 3 on the LCD screen [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To program the Arduino board, the LiquidCrystal I2C library is used to control the LCD screen, and the temperature sensor code is used to read the temperature from the sensor [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)]. The code is uploaded to the Arduino board using the Arduino IDE.

Overall, the LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a useful project for learning about Arduino programming and interfacing with sensors and displays. By following the instructions and code provided in the references, users can create their own system and experiment with different temperature sensors and LCD screens.

To support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens in Apache Airflow, you'll need to configure the `auth_backend` and `azure_active_directory` settings in your `airflow.cfg` file.

Here's an example configuration code snippet that you can use as a starting point:
```python
[core]
auth_backend = airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory

[azure_active_directory]
tenant_id = <your_tenant_id>
client_id = <your_client_id>
client_secret = <your_client_secret>
redirect_uri = <your_redirect_uri>
```
Replace the placeholders with your actual Azure AD application settings:

* `tenant_id`: Your Azure AD tenant ID.
* `client_id`: Your Azure AD application client ID.
* `client_secret`: Your Azure AD application client secret.
* `redirect_uri`: The redirect URI configured in your Azure AD application.

Additionally, you'll need to install the `azure-identity` and `azure-common` libraries, which are required for Azure AD authentication. You can install them using pip:
```bash
pip install azure-identity azure-common
```
Once you've updated your `airflow.cfg` file and installed the required libraries, restart your Airflow webserver and scheduler to apply the changes.

Example use case:

To test the Azure AD SSO token authentication, you can use the `airflow login` command with the `--auth` option, specifying the `azure_active_directory` auth backend:
```bash
airflow login --auth azure_active_directory
```

I have a string like this: `abc123def456`

I want to extract the first set of numbers, which is `123`.

How can I do this with a regex in javascript?

Answer: 

```javascript
const str = 'abc123def456';
const regex = /\d+/;
const match = str.match(regex);
console.log(match[0]); // outputs: 123
```

Explanation:

*   `\d` matches any digit (equivalent to `[0-9]`)
*   `+` matches one or more of the preceding token (in this case, `\d`)
*   `match()` returns an array containing the matched text if it finds a match, otherwise it returns `null`
*   `match[0]` returns the first (and in this case, the only) match

Note: This regex will match the first sequence of digits it encounters in the string.
